{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2017}} {|{{Infobox ship begin}} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header = |Ship country = [[United Kingdom]] |Ship flag = {{shipboxflag|UK|civil}} |Ship name = ''Speybank'' |Ship namesake = |Ship owner = |Ship operator = Andrew Weir & Co, [[London]] |Ship registry = |Ship route = |Ship ordered = |Ship awarded = |Ship builder = [[Harland and Wolff]], [[Glasgow]] |Ship original cost = |Ship yard number = 686 |Ship way number = |Ship laid down = |Ship launched = 25 February 1926 |Ship sponsor = |Ship christened = |Ship completed = |Ship acquired = |Ship maiden voyage = |Ship in service = |Ship out of service = |Ship renamed = ''Doggerbank'', 1941 |Ship refit = |Ship struck = |Ship homeport = |Ship motto = |Ship nickname = |Ship honors = |Ship fate = Captured by {{ship|German auxiliary cruiser|Atlantis}}, 31 January 1941 |Ship status = |Ship notes = |Ship badge = }} {{Infobox ship career |Hide header = title |Ship country = [[Nazi Germany]] |Ship flag = {{shipboxflag|Nazi Germany|naval}} |Ship name = ''Doggerbank'' |Ship namesake = [[Doggerbank]] |Ship ordered = |Ship builder = |Ship laid down = |Ship launched = |Ship acquired = |Ship commissioned = |Ship in service = 1941 |Ship out of service = |Ship struck = |Ship renamed = |Ship homeport = |Ship motto = |Ship nickname = |Ship honours = |Ship fate = Sunk by {{GS|U-43|1939|2}}, 3 March 1943 |Ship status = |Ship notes = }} {{Infobox ship characteristics |Hide header = <ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.clydesite.co.uk/clydebuilt/viewship.asp?id=5479 |title = ''Speybank'' |work = Clydebuilt Ships Database |accessdate = 16 May 2010 }}</ref> |Ship type = Merchant vessel |Ship tonnage = 5154 [[gross register tonnage|grt]] |Ship length = {{convert|420|ft|3|in|abbr=on}} |Ship beam = {{convert|53|ft|9|in|abbr=on}} |Ship draught = {{convert|26|ft|5|in|abbr=on}} |Ship depth = |Ship propulsion = marine [[Diesel engine]]s |Ship speed = |Ship range = |Ship complement = 108 (1943) |Ship sensors = |Ship EW = |Ship armament = |Ship notes = }} |}
The '''German ship ''Doggerbank'' (Schiff 53)''' was an auxiliary [[minelayer]] and [[blockade runner]] of [[Nazi Germany]] in [[World War II]].<ref name="Uboat" >{{cite web |url = http://uboat.net/allies/merchants/ships/2707.html |title = Ships hit by U-boats: ''Doggerbank'' |work = uboat.net |accessdate = 16 May 2010 }}</ref>
Laid down as the [[United Kingdom|UK]] [[merchant vessel]] '''''Speybank''''' in 1926, the vessel was captured in 1941 by the {{ship|German auxiliary cruiser|Atlantis}}, converted to an auxiliary minelayer for the ''[[Kriegsmarine]]'' and renamed ''Doggerbank''. After laying mines off the coast of [[South Africa]], it travelled to [[Japan]]. On the return trip, it was accidentally sunk by the {{ship|German submarine|U-43|1939|2|up=yes}}, with all but one of the 365 men on board (108 crew plus 257 prisoners-of-war) lost at sea.<ref name="Uboat"/>
==History== ''Speybank'' was built in 1926 at [[Harland & Wolff]] at [[Govan]], [[Glasgow]] for [[Andrew Weir, 1st Baron Inverforth|Andrew Weir]] & Co. The ship was captured on 31 January 1941 by German auxiliary cruiser ''Atlantis'' in the [[Indian Ocean]]. ''Speybank'' was sent back to [[France]] under the command of Paul Schneidewind and reached [[Bordeaux]] on 10 May 1941.<ref name="Uboat"/>
The ship was taken over by the German ''Kriegsmarine'' in 1941, renamed ''Doggerbank'' – ''Schiff 53'' (German: "Ship 53"), and converted to an auxiliary [[minelayer]]. It remained under the command of ''[[Captain Lieutenant|Kapitänleutnant]]'' Paul Schneidewind.<ref name="Uboat"/>
''Doggerbank'' left France in January 1942 to lay [[Naval mine|mines]] of the coast of South Africa and then to proceed to Japan. The mines were laid successfully in March/April 1942 and ''Doggerbank'' arrived in Japan later that year.
==Last voyage== In Japan, ''Doggerbank'' took aboard many of the survivors of the auxiliary cruiser {{ship|German auxiliary cruiser|Thor||2}} and the German tanker ''[[German tanker Altmark|Uckermark]]'', the former ''Altmark'', which had been destroyed in an accident in [[Yokohama]] on 30 November 1942. In total, the ship carried 365 men on board when leaving the Far East. It also carried a cargo of 7,000 tons of raw materials and rubber, fats and fish oil.<ref name="Uboat"/>
The ship travelled ''via'' [[Kobe]], [[Saigon]], [[Singapore]] and [[Jakarta]], which it left on 10 January 1943, heading to France. In the mid-Atlantic on 3 March 1943, at 9.53 pm, it was torpedoed by {{GS|U-43|1939|6}}. ''U-43'' mistook it for a British ship "of the {{MV|Dunedin Star||2}} type" as ''Doggerbank'' was traveling ahead of its schedule. The ship was hit by all three torpedoes fired at it and sank within two minutes,<ref name="Uboat"/> with perhaps two hundred men killed instantly.<ref>{{cite book |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=KvB6NPbSByAC |title = Google book preview: ''Lifeboat'' |page = 257 |accessdate = 16 May 2010 |ref = harv }}</ref>
==Aftermath== ''U-43'' observed five life boats being launched by the ship and attempted to make contact with the survivors, but failed to get close enough because of the darkness.<ref name="Uboat"/> Unaware of the ship's sinking as it had been unable to send a [[distress signal]], the German admiralty took days to realise the ship had been lost.
The eventual sole survivor of the crew of 108 and the 257 prisoners-of-war on board, Fritz Kürt, was in ''Doggerbank'''s [[jolly boat]], together with the ship's captain, Schneidewind, a small number of other men and the ship's dog. The boat headed for the [[South America]]n coast, approximately three weeks away. Through suicide and accidents, the small crew was eventually reduced to two, Kürt and an old sailor by the name of Boywitt, the captain having shot himself and the ship's dog having drowned. Desperate for water and food, Boywitt drank sea water on the 19th day of their journey and died, while Kürt was too weak to even roll the dead body overboard.<ref>{{cite web |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=KvB6NPbSByAC |title = Google books preview |last = Stilgoe |first = John |work = Lifeboat |page = 258 |accessdate = 16 May 2010 }}</ref> Kürt was eventually picked up by the [[Spain|Spanish]] motor tanker ''Campoamor'' on 29 March and taken to [[Aruba]].<ref name="Uboat"/>
The German submarine ''U-43'' was sunk on 30 July 1943 without survivors.<ref>{{cite web |url = http://www.uboat.net/boats/u43.htm |title = The Type IX boat U-43 |work = uboat.net |accessdate = 16 May 2010 }}</ref>
Kürt was exchanged in a prisoner-of-war swap in 1944, reported back to the German admiralty and then hid in [[Hamburg]] until the end of the war, having been about to be arrested.<ref>{{cite book |url = https://books.google.com/books?id=KvB6NPbSByAC |title = Google book preview: ''Lifeboat'' |page = 259 |accessdate = 16 May 2010 }}</ref>
