{{Infobox NRHP | name = Pickens Hall | nrhp_type = | image = | caption = | location= 83 State St., [[Heuvelton, New York]] | coordinates = {{coord|44|37|10|N|75|24|22|W|region:US_type:landmark|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = New York#USA | built = 1858 | architect = | architecture = Italianate | added = October 27, 2004 | area = less than one acre | governing_body = Private | refnum = 04001205<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2009a}}</ref> }} '''Pickens Hall''' was a [[vaudeville]] venue at [[Heuvelton, New York|Heuvelton]] in [[St. Lawrence County, New York]]. It was built in 1858 and is a three-story, rectangular stone building, 65 feet wide and 74 feet deep. It is an [[Italianate architecture|Italianate]] style building with commercial space on the first floor and office/storage rooms on the second floor. There is a General Store on the first floor, function space on the second, and a newly restored Opera House on the third floor which serves as a venue for various performances. The $2.75 million restoration project just received an "Excellence in Historic Preservation" award from the Preservation League of NY State.<ref name="NysNrhpNom">{{cite web | url = https://cris.parks.ny.gov/ | title = Cultural Resource Information System (CRIS)| publisher = [[New York State Office of Parks, Recreation and Historic Preservation]]| format = Searchable database| accessdate = 2016-08-01}} ''Note:'' This includes {{cite web | url = https://cris.parks.ny.gov/Uploads/ViewDoc.aspx?mode=A&id=23732&q=false | title = National Register of Historic Places Registration Form: Pickens Hall| accessdate = 2016-08-01 | author = Nancy L. Todd| format = PDF| date=June 2004}} and [https://cris.parks.ny.gov/Uploads/ViewDoc.aspx?mode=A&id=23734&q=false ''Accompanying photographs'']</ref>
It is listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]] in 2004.<ref name="nris"/>
In 2007 The Heuvelton Historical Association received a $50,000 state grant<ref>{{cite news |first= |last= |authorlink= |coauthors= |title=Wright secures $50,000 for Pickens Hall project. |url=http://www.accessmylibrary.com/coms2/summary_0286-32814342_ITM |quote=State Sen. James W. Wright, R-Watertown, secured the member-item grant for the association. The funding will be used to help match a $100,000 challenge grant from the Sweetgrass Foundation, said Graham D. Wise, chief of staff for Sen. Wright. |work=[[Watertown Daily Times]] |date=September 6, 2007 |accessdate=2009-12-06 }}</ref> to restore Pickens Hall which is now open as [http://pickensgeneral.org/ Pickens General Store].
