{{merge to|Dance party|date=November 2018}}
{{about|traditional play parties in the U.S.|BDSM play parties|play party (BDSM)}} A '''play party''' is a social event in which people gather to [[singing|sing]] and [[dance]]. Play parties began in the 1830s in the [[United States]] as a route around strict [[religion|religious]] practices banning dancing and the playing of [[musical instrument]]s. The areas most influenced by the practice were the Southern and Midwestern parts of the United States. [[Folk song]]s, many of [[Europe]]an and [[England|English]] origin, were used as means to give the attendants choreographed movements for each phrase. No instruments were played at the events, as they were banned by the religious movements of the area. Singing and clapping were used to convey each song. Because dancing was banned, the movements took on the quality of [[children's games]]. Though the performance of play parties dwindled in the 1950s, music educators use them as ways to incorporate music and dance in their classrooms.<ref>{{cite book | last = Spurgeon | first = Alan L | authorlink = | coauthors = | title = Waltz the Hall: The American Play Party | publisher =University of Mississippi Press | date = | location = | pages = 256 | url = http://www.upress.state.ms.us/books/792 | doi = | id = | isbn = 978-1-60473-381-5}} </ref>
Some traditional examples of play-parties are: [[Skip to My Lou]], [[Buffalo Gals]], [[Bingo (folk song)|Bingo]], [[Pop Goes the Weasel]], [[Old Dan Tucker]], Coffee Grows on White Oak Trees, Shoot the Buffalo, etc.
